<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="215" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="20.[813,1456,405,535]" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">
DIAGNOSIS. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[932,957,405,429]" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">—</emphasis>
A blind, colourless species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vandel" authorityYear="1946" box="[1247,1352,406,430]" class="Malacostraca" family="Armadillidiidae" genus="Trogleluma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="20" pageNumber="215" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1247,1352,406,430]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Trogleluma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
characterized by dorsal surface covered with piliform scale-setae, uropodal exopod with parallel sides, male pereopod 7 ischium with concave sternal margin, male pleopod 1 exopod triangular with broadly rounded apex and some setae near inner margin.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="215" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="20.[813,1455,568,619]" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">
ETYMOLOGY. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[946,971,568,592]" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">—</emphasis>
From the Latin 
<emphasis box="[1130,1191,568,592]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">pilosus</emphasis>
= hairy. The name refers to the dorsal surface covered with long piliform scale-setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="20" pageNumber="215" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="20.[813,1456,663,1551]" box="[813,957,663,689]" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[813,1456,663,1551]" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">
Maximum length: 
<specimenCount box="[1021,1044,698,723]" pageId="20" pageNumber="215" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
, 
<quantity box="[1058,1127,695,722]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="20" pageNumber="215" unit="mm" value="5.0">5 mm</quantity>
; 
<specimenCount box="[1139,1159,698,723]" pageId="20" pageNumber="215" type="female">♀</specimenCount>
, 
<quantity box="[1173,1265,695,722]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="20" pageNumber="215" unit="mm" value="5.5">5.5 mm</quantity>
. Body colourless, strongly convex, able to roll up into a perfect ball (
<figureCitation box="[1345,1441,727,754]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="21.[132,143,1987,2005]" captionTargetBox="[132,1430,231,1814]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[132,1455,216,1819]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIG. 15. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio, ♀ paratype: A, adult specimen, lateral view; B, dorsal scale-seta; C, cephalon, frontal view; D, cephalon, dorsal view; E, epimeron of pereonite 1, dorsal view; F, telson and uropods, dorsal view; G, antennula; H, antenna. Scale bar: A, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741532" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3741532/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Fig. 15A</figureCitation>
), dorsally covered with long piliform scale-setae (
<figureCitation box="[1342,1442,759,786]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="21.[132,143,1987,2005]" captionTargetBox="[132,1430,231,1814]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[132,1455,216,1819]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIG. 15. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio, ♀ paratype: A, adult specimen, lateral view; B, dorsal scale-seta; C, cephalon, frontal view; D, cephalon, dorsal view; E, epimeron of pereonite 1, dorsal view; F, telson and uropods, dorsal view; G, antennula; H, antenna. Scale bar: A, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741532" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3741532/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Fig. 15B</figureCitation>
); one line of noduli laterales per side on pereonites, more or less at the same distance from lateral margin (
<figureCitation box="[1338,1442,823,850]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="21.[132,143,1987,2005]" captionTargetBox="[132,1430,231,1814]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[132,1455,216,1819]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIG. 15. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio, ♀ paratype: A, adult specimen, lateral view; B, dorsal scale-seta; C, cephalon, frontal view; D, cephalon, dorsal view; E, epimeron of pereonite 1, dorsal view; F, telson and uropods, dorsal view; G, antennula; H, antenna. Scale bar: A, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741532" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3741532/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Fig. 15A</figureCitation>
). Cephalon (
<figureCitation box="[940,1082,855,882]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="21.[132,143,1987,2005]" captionTargetBox="[132,1430,231,1814]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[132,1455,216,1819]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIG. 15. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio, ♀ paratype: A, adult specimen, lateral view; B, dorsal scale-seta; C, cephalon, frontal view; D, cephalon, dorsal view; E, epimeron of pereonite 1, dorsal view; F, telson and uropods, dorsal view; G, antennula; H, antenna. Scale bar: A, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741532" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3741532/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Fig. 15C, D</figureCitation>
) with a V-shaped scutellum and continuous frontal line; antennary lobes oblique; eyes absent. Pereonite 1 (
<figureCitation box="[1012,1109,919,946]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="21.[132,143,1987,2005]" captionTargetBox="[132,1430,231,1814]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[132,1455,216,1819]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIG. 15. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio, ♀ paratype: A, adult specimen, lateral view; B, dorsal scale-seta; C, cephalon, frontal view; D, cephalon, dorsal view; E, epimeron of pereonite 1, dorsal view; F, telson and uropods, dorsal view; G, antennula; H, antenna. Scale bar: A, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741532" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3741532/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Fig. 15E</figureCitation>
) with posterior margin slightly concave at sides; no schisma on postero-lateral margin and with small ventral tooth. Telson (
<figureCitation box="[1188,1286,982,1009]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="21.[132,143,1987,2005]" captionTargetBox="[132,1430,231,1814]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[132,1455,216,1819]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIG. 15. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio, ♀ paratype: A, adult specimen, lateral view; B, dorsal scale-seta; C, cephalon, frontal view; D, cephalon, dorsal view; E, epimeron of pereonite 1, dorsal view; F, telson and uropods, dorsal view; G, antennula; H, antenna. Scale bar: A, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741532" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3741532/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Fig. 15F</figureCitation>
) subtriangular, as wide as long, with slightly concave sides and rounded apex. Antennula (
<figureCitation box="[1007,1108,1046,1073]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="21.[132,143,1987,2005]" captionTargetBox="[132,1430,231,1814]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[132,1455,216,1819]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIG. 15. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio, ♀ paratype: A, adult specimen, lateral view; B, dorsal scale-seta; C, cephalon, frontal view; D, cephalon, dorsal view; E, epimeron of pereonite 1, dorsal view; F, telson and uropods, dorsal view; G, antennula; H, antenna. Scale bar: A, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741532" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3741532/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Fig. 15G</figureCitation>
) of three articles, second article shortest, two subapical rows with nine aestethacs in total and pointed apex. Antenna (
<figureCitation box="[1143,1250,1110,1137]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="21.[132,143,1987,2005]" captionTargetBox="[132,1430,231,1814]" captionTargetId="figure@21.[132,1455,216,1819]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIG. 15. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio, ♀ paratype: A, adult specimen, lateral view; B, dorsal scale-seta; C, cephalon, frontal view; D, cephalon, dorsal view; E, epimeron of pereonite 1, dorsal view; F, telson and uropods, dorsal view; G, antennula; H, antenna. Scale bar: A, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741532" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3741532/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Fig. 15H</figureCitation>
) with fifth article of peduncle slightly longer than flagellum; second flagellar article about three times as long as first bearing three rows of aesthetascs. Mandibles (
<figureCitation box="[1102,1230,1206,1232]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="22.[133,144,1357,1375]" captionTargetBox="[144,1415,215,1296]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[132,1455,198,1307]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIG. 16. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio,♀ paratype:A, left mandible; B, right mandible;C, maxillula; D, maxilla;E, maxilliped;F, left uropod." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741534" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3741534/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Fig. 16A, B</figureCitation>
) with molar penicils semidichotomized and 2+ 3 penicils on the left and 1 + 3 on the right mandible. Maxillula (
<figureCitation box="[1147,1244,1269,1296]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="22.[133,144,1357,1375]" captionTargetBox="[144,1415,215,1296]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[132,1455,198,1307]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIG. 16. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio,♀ paratype:A, left mandible; B, right mandible;C, maxillula; D, maxilla;E, maxilliped;F, left uropod." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741534" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3741534/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Fig. 16C</figureCitation>
) outer branch with 4+ 6 (5 cleft) teeth, inner branch with two slender penicils. Maxilla (
<figureCitation box="[909,1009,1333,1360]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="22.[133,144,1357,1375]" captionTargetBox="[144,1415,215,1296]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[132,1455,198,1307]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIG. 16. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio,♀ paratype:A, left mandible; B, right mandible;C, maxillula; D, maxilla;E, maxilliped;F, left uropod." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741534" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3741534/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Fig. 16D</figureCitation>
) with bilobed and setose apex, outer lobe wider than inner one. Maxilliped (
<figureCitation box="[1180,1273,1365,1392]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="22.[133,144,1357,1375]" captionTargetBox="[144,1415,215,1296]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[132,1455,198,1307]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIG. 16. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio,♀ paratype:A, left mandible; B, right mandible;C, maxillula; D, maxilla;E, maxilliped;F, left uropod." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741534" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3741534/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Fig. 16E</figureCitation>
) endite with two triangular terminal spines, one subterminal strong seta. Pleopod 1 and 2 exopods with monospiracular covered lungs. Uropod (
<figureCitation box="[919,1019,1461,1488]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="22.[133,144,1357,1375]" captionTargetBox="[144,1415,215,1296]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[132,1455,198,1307]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIG. 16. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio,♀ paratype:A, left mandible; B, right mandible;C, maxillula; D, maxilla;E, maxilliped;F, left uropod." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741534" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3741534/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Fig. 16F</figureCitation>
) protopod as long as exopod; exopod rectangular, flattened, longer than wide with parallel sides; endopod slightly longer than exopod.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[813,1456,1588,1902]" box="[813,866,1588,1614]" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">
<emphasis box="[813,866,1588,1614]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Male</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[813,1456,1588,1902]" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">
Pereopod 1 (
<figureCitation box="[957,1059,1620,1646]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="23.[132,143,1527,1545]" captionTargetBox="[141,1450,230,1448]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[131,1454,212,1458]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIG. 17. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio, ♂ holotype: A, perepod 1; B, pereopod 7; C, pleopod 1; D, pleopod 2; E, pleopod 3 exopod; F, pleopod 4 exopod; G, pleopod 5 exopod." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741536" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3741536/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Fig. 17A</figureCitation>
) with some strong setae on sternal margin of merus and carpus. Pereopod 7 (
<figureCitation box="[1261,1355,1652,1678]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="23.[132,143,1527,1545]" captionTargetBox="[141,1450,230,1448]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[131,1454,212,1458]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIG. 17. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio, ♂ holotype: A, perepod 1; B, pereopod 7; C, pleopod 1; D, pleopod 2; E, pleopod 3 exopod; F, pleopod 4 exopod; G, pleopod 5 exopod." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741536" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3741536/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Fig. 17B</figureCitation>
) ischium with concave sternal margin. Pleopod 1 (
<figureCitation box="[1261,1360,1684,1710]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="23.[132,143,1527,1545]" captionTargetBox="[141,1450,230,1448]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[131,1454,212,1458]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIG. 17. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio, ♂ holotype: A, perepod 1; B, pereopod 7; C, pleopod 1; D, pleopod 2; E, pleopod 3 exopod; F, pleopod 4 exopod; G, pleopod 5 exopod." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741536" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3741536/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Fig. 17C</figureCitation>
) exopod triangular with broadly rounded apex and some setae near inner margin; endopod with pointed apex, slightly bent outwards and bearing a row of short setae. Pleopod 2 (
<figureCitation box="[1349,1446,1780,1806]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="23.[132,143,1527,1545]" captionTargetBox="[141,1450,230,1448]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[131,1454,212,1458]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIG. 17. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio, ♂ holotype: A, perepod 1; B, pereopod 7; C, pleopod 1; D, pleopod 2; E, pleopod 3 exopod; F, pleopod 4 exopod; G, pleopod 5 exopod." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741536" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3741536/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Fig. 17D</figureCitation>
) exopod triangular much longer than wide; endopod elongated and much longer than exopod. Pleopod 3-5 exopods as in 
<figureCitation box="[813,886,1875,1902]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="23.[132,143,1527,1545]" captionTargetBox="[141,1450,230,1448]" captionTargetId="figure@23.[131,1454,212,1458]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIG. 17. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio, ♂ holotype: A, perepod 1; B, pereopod 7; C, pleopod 1; D, pleopod 2; E, pleopod 3 exopod; F, pleopod 4 exopod; G, pleopod 5 exopod." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741536" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3741536/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Fig. 17</figureCitation>
E-G.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="217" pageId="20" pageNumber="215" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="20.[813,1455,1939,2030]" box="[813,913,1939,1965]" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="20.[813,1455,1939,2030]" lastBlockId="22.[132,775,1429,1838]" lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="217" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vandel" authorityYear="1946" box="[813,932,1971,1997]" class="Malacostraca" family="Armadillidiidae" genus="Trogleluma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="20" pageNumber="215" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[813,932,1971,1997]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Trogleluma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was erected by 
<bibRefCitation author="Vandel" box="[1107,1267,1971,1998]" firstAuthor="Vandel" pageId="20" pageNumber="215" pagination="135 - 427" refId="ref13156" refString="VANDEL A. 1946. - Crustaces isopodes terrestres (Oniscoidea) epiges et cavernicoles du Portugal. Etude des recoltes de Monsieur A. de Barros Machado. Anais da Faculdade de Ciencias do Porto 30: 135 - 427." type="journal article" year="1946">Vandel (1946)</bibRefCitation>
as a subgenus of 
<taxonomicName authority="Verhoeff, 1900" authorityName="Verhoeff" authorityYear="1900" box="[813,1193,2003,2029]" class="Malacostraca" family="Armadillidiidae" genus="Troglarmadillidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="20" pageNumber="215" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[813,1023,2003,2029]" italics="true" pageId="20" pageNumber="215">Troglarmadillidium</emphasis>
Verhoeff, 1900
</taxonomicName>
to include the new spe- cies 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vandel" authorityYear="1946" box="[180,647,1429,1456]" class="Malacostraca" family="Armadillidiidae" genus="Troglarmadillidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="217" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="machadoi" subGenus="Trogleluma">
<emphasis box="[180,390,1429,1455]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="217">Troglarmadillidium</emphasis>
(
<emphasis box="[408,527,1429,1455]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="217">Trogleluma</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis box="[545,647,1429,1455]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="217">machadoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from caves in southern 
<collectingCountry box="[273,368,1461,1487]" name="Portugal" pageId="22" pageNumber="217">Portugal</collectingCountry>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="Reboleira" box="[384,642,1461,1488]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Reboleira" pageId="22" pageNumber="217" pagination="1 - 61" refId="ref11964" refString="REBOLEIRA A. S. P. S., GONCALVES F., OROMI P. &amp; TAITI S. 2015. - The cavernicolous Oniscidea (Crustacea: Isopoda) of Portugal. European Journal of Taxonomy 161: 1 - 61. https: // doi. org / 10.5852 / ejt. 2015.161" type="journal article" year="2015">
Reboleira 
<emphasis box="[501,556,1461,1487]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="217">et al.</emphasis>
(2015)
</bibRefCitation>
raised it to genus level and redescribed the 
<typeStatus box="[495,543,1493,1519]" pageId="22" pageNumber="217">type</typeStatus>
species which is the only species in the genus presently known. The new species differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Vandel" authorityYear="1946" box="[317,449,1556,1582]" class="Malacostraca" family="Armadillidiidae" genus="Troglarmadillidium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Isopoda" pageId="22" pageNumber="217" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="machadoi">
<emphasis box="[317,449,1556,1582]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="217">T. machadoi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having piliform instead of triangular dorsal scale-setae, the telson with more rounded apex, the male pereopod 7 ischium with concave, instead of straight, sternal margin, the male pleopod 1 exopod with a more pronounced distal part, and the male pleopod 2 exopod with slightly, instead of deeply, concave outer margin (compare 
<figureCitation box="[247,369,1748,1775]" captionStart-0="FIG" captionStart-1="FIG" captionStart-2="FIG" captionStartId-0="21.[132,143,1987,2005]" captionStartId-1="22.[133,144,1357,1375]" captionStartId-2="23.[132,143,1527,1545]" captionTargetBox-0="[132,1430,231,1814]" captionTargetBox-1="[144,1415,215,1296]" captionTargetBox-2="[141,1450,230,1448]" captionTargetId-0="figure@21.[132,1455,216,1819]" captionTargetId-1="figure@22.[132,1455,198,1307]" captionTargetId-2="figure@23.[131,1454,212,1458]" captionTargetPageId-0="21" captionTargetPageId-1="22" captionTargetPageId-2="23" captionText-0="FIG. 15. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio, ♀ paratype: A, adult specimen, lateral view; B, dorsal scale-seta; C, cephalon, frontal view; D, cephalon, dorsal view; E, epimeron of pereonite 1, dorsal view; F, telson and uropods, dorsal view; G, antennula; H, antenna. Scale bar: A, 1 mm." captionText-1="FIG. 16. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio,♀ paratype:A, left mandible; B, right mandible;C, maxillula; D, maxilla;E, maxilliped;F, left uropod." captionText-2="FIG. 17. — Trogleluma pilosa n. sp., from Poggio Capalbiaccio, ♂ holotype: A, perepod 1; B, pereopod 7; C, pleopod 1; D, pleopod 2; E, pleopod 3 exopod; F, pleopod 4 exopod; G, pleopod 5 exopod." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741532" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741534" figureDoi-2="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3741536" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/3741532/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/3741534/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/3741536/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="217">Figs 15-17</figureCitation>
with 
<bibRefCitation author="Reboleira" box="[437,675,1748,1775]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Reboleira" pageId="22" pageNumber="217" pagination="1 - 61" refId="ref11964" refString="REBOLEIRA A. S. P. S., GONCALVES F., OROMI P. &amp; TAITI S. 2015. - The cavernicolous Oniscidea (Crustacea: Isopoda) of Portugal. European Journal of Taxonomy 161: 1 - 61. https: // doi. org / 10.5852 / ejt. 2015.161" type="journal article" year="2015">
Reboleira 
<emphasis box="[553,608,1748,1774]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="217">et al.</emphasis>
2015
</bibRefCitation>
: figs 33, 34). The record of this new species considerably enlarges the distribution of the genus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
